                To achive the best finish, the process starts with making the body smooth and ready for paint application.
                A very thin skim of polyester body filler is the start. The initial filler is worked with a sanding block or body file, reapplying filler as needed.</p>
                <p>Once the repair is satisfactorily feathered-in with the surrounding metal, it can be sanded progressively finer in preparation for the primer-surfacer coat. If sanding alone does not clean the filled surface, another coat of filler or a glaze coat can be applied.
